  "text": "The second approach is to improve ethanol yields by genetic engineering of microorganisms that already have the ability to ferment both hexoses and pentoses [CITATION_1] . There are some examples of success in engineering of Gram-negative bacteria such as Escherichia coli and Klebsiella oxytoca that are naturally able to use a wide spectrum of sugars, including xylose, to produce ethanol [CITATION_2] . Although this approach has been experimentally successful, unfortunately rates and yields of ethanol on mixed sugars derived from lignocellulosic biomass have not been commercially feasible to date.",
